    <text>
    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>April 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I am very much obliged for your kind letter of March 19<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>— But your information is not new to me, as I read with <hi rend="underline">great</hi> interest your first &amp; second published notice on the case.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> It seems to me a very strange one, &amp; different from any other known to me.—</p>
                    <p>I remain Dear Sir | with much respect. | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.2 published] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Loomis had sent observations on the spontaneous movements of the fern <hi rend="italic">Asplenium trichomanes</hi> (maidenhair spleenwort); see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13090.xml">letter from E. J. Loomis, [19 March 1881]</ref>. Short pieces by Loomis on these movements were communicated by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1957.xml">Asa Gray</ref> to the <hi rend="italic">Botanical Gazette</hi> 5 (1880): 27 and 43. CD had cited the case in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5637.xml"><hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi></ref>, pp. 257–8 n.</note>
        </div>
    
